    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nVim stores two curswant values.\n\nThe current window curswant can only be accessed (AFAIK) by using getcurpos() or winsaveview(), both of which return other data.\n\nA vi_curswant value is also held in the buffer data, containing the curswant of the previous visual selection. If you are trying to build accurate region data based on the '<'> marks, the vi_curswant value is necessary for visual block selections to determine if they should extend to the end of the line.\n\nThe only way I know of to get this value is to re-enter visual mode so that the window curswant is set to vi_curswant.\n\n(The hl.on_yank function masks this limitation because it takes the full regtype as a parameter and passes that to getregionpos, which parses the block width from there)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIntroduce the following API:\n\n```lua\n---@class vim.api.keyset.curswant\n---@field win? integer\n---@field buf? integer\n\n--- Get the curswant value of the specified scope.\n---\n--- Note the options {win} and {buf} cannot be used together.\n--- If opts is empty or not provided, the curswant of the current window will be returned\n---\n---@param opts? vim.api.keyset.curswant Optional parameters\n--- - win: `window-ID` Get the window's current curswant value \n--- - buf: Buffer number. Get the buffer's stored curswant from its previous visual selection\n---@return integer\nfunction vim.api.nvim_get_curswant(opts) end\n```\n\nMinimal alternative: Add vi_curswant as a return to getbufinfo(), which would still be a lighter operation than re-entering visual mode.",
